<h3 id="projects">Research Projects</h3>

<hr>

<div>
    <img id="meprecisa" src="/images/meprecisa.png" height="60" alt="MePreCiSa">
    <div>I coordinated the <a href="https://meprecisa.com/" target="_blank">MePreCiSa project</a> (2023–2025), funded through the UNICO I+D Cloud programme by the Spanish Ministry for Digital Transformation and Public Administration and the European Union – NextGenerationEU. The project aimed to develop an open cloud platform for health management in complex urban environments by integrating mobility, environmental, and epidemiological data. The platform combined AI-, data-driven, and simulation-based technologies to support predictive analytics, urban health studies, epidemic preparedness, and decision-making. My work focused on the development of epidemic simulation and data analysis workflows, including mobility-informed epidemiological modeling and large-scale HPC-enabled simulations for outbreak analysis and intervention assessment.</div>
</div>

<hr>

<div>
    <img id="crexdata" src="/images/crexdata.png" height="60" alt="CREXDATA">
    <div>I participated in the EU-funded <a href="https://cordis.europa.eu/project/id/101092749" target="_blank">CREXDATA project</a> (2022–2025), in which we develop a versatile platform for real-time critical situation management, adaptive action planning, and agile decision-making powered by extreme-scale and complex data (<a href="https://crexdata.eu/">https://crexdata.eu/</a>). The platform combined AI-, data-driven, and simulation-based technologies to support crisis analysis and forecasting across multiple domains. I led the Health Crisis use case, where we developed EpiSim.jl, an HPC-enabled epidemic simulation framework for large-scale epidemiological modeling, calibration, uncertainty quantification, and intervention optimization.</div>
</div>

<hr>

<div>
    <img id="permedcoe" src="/images/permedcoe.png" height="120" alt="PerMedCoE">
    <div>I participated in the <a href="https://permedcoe.eu" target="_blank">PerMedCoE project</a> (2020–2023), funded by the European Union’s Horizon 2020 research and innovation programme under grant agreement No. 951773. The project aimed to provide an efficient and sustainable entry point to HPC and exascale technologies for personalized medicine by translating omics data into actionable mechanistic models of cellular behavior. PerMedCoE combined HPC, AI-, data-driven, and simulation-based methodologies to enable large-scale cell-level simulations and predictive workflows for biomedical research. My contribution focused on the development and optimization of multicellular and mechanistic simulation workflows for cancer research, including HPC-enabled analyses of tumor dynamics, drug response, and multiscale biological systems.</div>
</div>
<hr>
<div>
    <img id="infore" src="/images/infore.png" height="40" alt="INFORE">
    <div>I participated in the INFORE project (2019–2022), funded by the European Union’s Horizon 2020 research and innovation programme under grant agreement No. 825070. The project aimed to develop technologies for interactive extreme-scale analytics and forecasting over massive streaming datasets, combining HPC, AI, machine learning, and data-driven workflows for real-time decision support. The INFORE platform was applied to domains including life sciences, finance, and maritime situational awareness. My contribution focused on the Life Sciences use case, where I worked on large-scale multicellular and cancer simulation workflows, HPC-enabled data analysis, and predictive modeling for studying tumor growth and drug synergies.</div>
</div>

